7.  Once we have added all the edges to the minimum spanning tree, we can calculate the total weight of the minimum spanning tree by summing up the weights of all the edges in the tree.
8.  Since the graph is a complete graph, the total number of edges is n(n-1)/2. Therefore, the total weight of the minimum spanning tree is equal to the number of edges in the tree (which is m) plus the number of edges that are not in the tree (which is n(n-1)/2 - m).

